1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,380
This lesson goes into a bit more detail about the concepts of figures,

2
00:00:04,380 --> 00:00:07,440
axes and subplots in matplotlib.

3
00:00:07,440 --> 00:00:09,630
This is an area of much confusion with

4
00:00:09,630 --> 00:00:12,450
new analyst because it's not always made clear what

5
00:00:12,450 --> 00:00:17,895
the difference between a figure object and an axis is and how to interact with each.

6
00:00:17,895 --> 00:00:21,000
But don't worry, it really isn't confusing.

7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,135
We'll start simple and build up from there.

8
00:00:24,135 --> 00:00:29,715
This is also a good time to note that seaborne is actually built on-top of matplotlib.

9
00:00:29,715 --> 00:00:32,340
These concepts apply to it as well.

10
00:00:32,340 --> 00:00:35,490
Remember, anything you can do with matplotlib,

11
00:00:35,490 --> 00:00:38,835
you can also do to seaborne with a little work.

12
00:00:38,835 --> 00:00:42,590
Let's start by importing our typical libraries and

13
00:00:42,590 --> 00:00:46,980
also the diamond dataset to give us something to play with.

14
00:00:49,850 --> 00:00:54,050
Now, the normal way most people interact with pyplot,

15
00:00:54,050 --> 00:00:56,600
that's the main library of matplotlib,

16
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:59,440
is through pyplot functions.

17
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:03,150
Remember, we import these as PLT.

18
00:01:03,150 --> 00:01:05,840
When you begin plotting anything,

19
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:09,500
the first thing that happens is a figure object is created.

20
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:12,230
For instance, when plotting a histogram,

21
00:01:12,230 --> 00:01:17,255
it creates a figure that's the canvas that this is drawn on.

22
00:01:17,255 --> 00:01:19,640
Then it draws a set of axes,

23
00:01:19,640 --> 00:01:22,880
and then finally, the histogram on that axis.

24
00:01:22,880 --> 00:01:27,505
It does all of this at once under the hood, so to speak.

25
00:01:27,505 --> 00:01:32,450
We can start just by plotting or creating a figure directly.

26
00:01:32,450 --> 00:01:36,400
Notice I am not plotting the trailing semicolon here,

27
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:38,775
so we get the plotting artifacts.

28
00:01:38,775 --> 00:01:46,910
We see that it creates a figure of size 400 by 300 pixels with zero axes on top.

29
00:01:46,910 --> 00:01:48,830
If we want to go further,

30
00:01:48,830 --> 00:01:54,305
we can take this figure object and specifically set the access locations.

31
00:01:54,305 --> 00:01:57,485
For instance, when we create a figure,

32
00:01:57,485 --> 00:02:00,680
we can save it into a figure object,

33
00:02:00,680 --> 00:02:06,500
and then we can add the axes locations specifically here.

34
00:02:06,500 --> 00:02:08,810
Then on top of that axes,

35
00:02:08,810 --> 00:02:11,420
we can then plot our histogram.

36
00:02:11,420 --> 00:02:16,835
The Add Axes function is useful if you really want to get into customizing your plots.

37
00:02:16,835 --> 00:02:20,210
Typically during explanatory analysis.

38
00:02:20,210 --> 00:02:23,660
Often though, the default locations suffice.

39
00:02:23,660 --> 00:02:27,260
But it's really worth experimenting with passing in

40
00:02:27,260 --> 00:02:32,705
various locations to get a feel for how this works and what it looks like when you do.

41
00:02:32,705 --> 00:02:36,560
Now, if you want to create two subplots within a figure,

42
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:40,900
you can use the pyplot method subplot.

43
00:02:40,900 --> 00:02:44,960
This specifies n rows and m columns,

44
00:02:44,960 --> 00:02:48,265
and then you can use it to iterate through each.

45
00:02:48,265 --> 00:02:53,300
For instance, if we'd like to plot a grid of four histograms,

46
00:02:53,300 --> 00:02:59,270
we can do that by creating our figure and then calling subplot.

47
00:02:59,270 --> 00:03:03,140
Here, we'll have two rows and two columns,

48
00:03:03,140 --> 00:03:06,805
and we want to take just subplot number 1.

49
00:03:06,805 --> 00:03:08,765
Now, in this example,

50
00:03:08,765 --> 00:03:13,280
I actually skipped Subplots 2 and 3 to show you what it looks like.

51
00:03:13,280 --> 00:03:15,065
You don't have to plot them all.

52
00:03:15,065 --> 00:03:18,745
Here. I just plot Subplot 1,

53
00:03:18,745 --> 00:03:20,060
which is the upper left,

54
00:03:20,060 --> 00:03:23,015
and subplot four, which is the lower right.

55
00:03:23,015 --> 00:03:28,295
You can see here we created our canvas with four subplots,

56
00:03:28,295 --> 00:03:30,580
but we're only using two currently.

57
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:33,350
That said, there is another way to interact with

58
00:03:33,350 --> 00:03:37,715
plots and that's interacting with a specific access object.

59
00:03:37,715 --> 00:03:43,015
Let's start by comparing what happens when you call pyplot directly.

60
00:03:43,015 --> 00:03:47,510
Here we call pyplot directly calling the histogram function,

61
00:03:47,510 --> 00:03:55,830
and then we want to set the x-axis label and also call pyplot directly.

62
00:03:56,940 --> 00:04:01,975
Alternatively, we can use the pyplot function,

63
00:04:01,975 --> 00:04:08,005
get current access or GCA to retrieve the axes object,

64
00:04:08,005 --> 00:04:12,415
and then we can use the access function set

65
00:04:12,415 --> 00:04:17,745
underscore x-label to set the x-label directly.

66
00:04:17,745 --> 00:04:23,185
Note the difference is only a slightly different calling syntax.

67
00:04:23,185 --> 00:04:29,455
One can interact with the figure directly using the pyplot functions.

68
00:04:29,455 --> 00:04:32,470
If there were multiple subplots in the figure and

69
00:04:32,470 --> 00:04:35,965
axon whatever the current active subplot is.

70
00:04:35,965 --> 00:04:38,980
Or if you have a specific axis,

71
00:04:38,980 --> 00:04:45,650
like this example, you can just interact or operate directly on it.

72
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:51,310
I find the axis notation to be convenient for two reasons.

73
00:04:51,310 --> 00:04:54,130
One, if you want to create subplots,

74
00:04:54,130 --> 00:04:56,155
you can act on them individually.

75
00:04:56,155 --> 00:04:58,415
You don't have to iterate through them.

76
00:04:58,415 --> 00:05:03,745
For example, if you use the pyplot function subplots.

77
00:05:03,745 --> 00:05:07,570
Notice this is subplots with an S. You can

78
00:05:07,570 --> 00:05:11,005
specify the number of rows and the number of columns,

79
00:05:11,005 --> 00:05:13,360
and also the figure size directly.

80
00:05:13,360 --> 00:05:21,090
This returns both the figure object and an array of axes objects.

81
00:05:21,090 --> 00:05:25,025
If you want to plot two subplots next to each other,

82
00:05:25,025 --> 00:05:28,100
you can just pass those directly to

83
00:05:28,100 --> 00:05:32,620
seaborne or to matplotlib to operate directly on them.

84
00:05:32,620 --> 00:05:34,535
Just like this.

85
00:05:34,535 --> 00:05:40,775
Alternatively, seaborne typically returns axes objects.

86
00:05:40,775 --> 00:05:43,160
if you don't specify the axes,

87
00:05:43,160 --> 00:05:45,365
when you create a seaborne plot,

88
00:05:45,365 --> 00:05:50,975
you can just retrieve the axis from the function call and then

89
00:05:50,975 --> 00:05:57,960
operate directly on it to set whatever labels or adjustments you feel are necessary.

